article.description: Andrei Kirilenko had 21 points and 12 rebounds and Mehmet Okur shot 8-for-8 in scoring a season-high 20 points to lead the host Utah Jazz over the Houston Rockets 90-80 Friday.
article.headline: Houston loses four of last six games
article.linkText: Kirilenko, Okur pace Jazz over Rockets
article.story:
SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Mehmet Okur sunk an improbable baseline jumper over Yao Ming, a perfect ending to a perfect shooting game. Okur, who signed a six-year free agent contract with Utah over the summer, had his best game with the Jazz by scoring a season-high 20 points on 8-of-8 shooting as Utah defeated Houston 90-80 Friday night. "I felt good, especially playing against a big guy like Yao Ming. Tonight I could take the 3-pointer or put the ball on the floor and make foul shots," said Okur, who played only 25 minutes and has yet to start for the Jazz. Yao acknowledged he struggled with Okur's agility and said, "On any team he plays for he could star, but he plays [off the ] bench for the Utah Jazz and makes them much stronger." Andrei Kirilenko, playing with a renewed enthusiasm that was missing as the Jazz dropped four of their previous five games, had 21 points and 12 rebounds. He also had four blocks and three steals as Utah held Houston to 37 percent shooting. Kirilenko "dominates the stat sheet and has a lot of energy. It seems he doesn't have a defensive assignment. He was just all over the place blocking shots on the weak side. He has great instincts," said Tracy McGrady, who had 17 points. Jim Jackson scored 18 points for the Rockets, who have lost four of their last six games. Houston launched 28 3-point attempts, making eight, as the inside game was noticeably absent. Yao had only nine points and four rebounds. As Yao struggled, Okur thrived. "He shot the ball very well," Utah coach Jerry Sloan said. "He knows how to get open." "Once he got on a roll, he was on a roll. Everything fell for him tonight," said Carlos Boozer, who had 15 points. The Jazz, who led the league in field goal shooting before its recent swoon, shot 50 percent and had 27 assists on 36 field goals. "We set more screens to try and help other people instead of thinking about ourselves. We passed the ball better and executed our offense," Sloan said. Jackson's driving dunk got Houston to 80-75 with 4:18 to play, but Carlos Arroyo and Okur each hit a pair of jumpers while the Rockets missed a flurry of outside shots. "Okur is a tough matchup for our centers and he did a good job exploiting that," Houston coach Jeff Van Gundy said. Utah's victory came after consecutive home losses against previously winless New Orleans and Chicago. With a lineup comprised mostly of reserves to start the fourth quarter, the Rockets drew to 74-69 on 3-pointers by Scott Padgett and Jackson. Spurred by Okur's 12 second-quarter points on 5-of-5 shooting, the Jazz took a 50-40 lead into halftime and never relinquished it. "They just outplayed us from the first quarter on. They had their way with us," Van Gundy said. After averaging 22 points and nine rebounds over a five-game stretch, Yao was hampered by early foul trouble and never found his rhythm. Starting power forward Maurice Taylor didn't score for the Rockets, shooting 0 for-7, in the final game of their four-game road trip.

Game notes
Charlie Ward, who missed the Rockets' loss at Sacramento on Wednesday with a sore right knee, started and played with a heavy wrap on the leg. He had 3 points. ... University of Utah football coach Urban Meyer, whose Utes are 11-0, sat courtside and received an ovation. ... Houston's season-long streak of reaching 90 points was snapped at four games. ... A career 68-percent free throw shooter, Dikembe Mutombo is now 14-of-15 for the season. ... The loss kept Van Gundy from reaching his 300th career win.
